occurrences.line_text: Where was her won, and how he mote her find.
Vnto the rocke, where was the villains won:
And th'actours won the meede meet for their crymes.
Where curteous Knights and Ladies most did won
These goodly gilden armes, which I haue won in fight.
Where was his won; ne did the other stay,
The spoiles of Princes hang'd, which were in battel won.
The glorie of the great, mongst whom I won,
And comming down to seeke them, where they wond,
Into this land, where I haue wond thus long,
And wonder of her beautie soueraine,
That wonder was to heare her goodly speach:
No wonder if he wondred at the sight,
Ne wonder; for her owne deare loued knight,
Did wonder much at her celestiall sight:
He wo[n]der would much more: yet such to some appeare.
And into diuerse doubt his wauering wonder cloue.
But th'Elfin knight with wonder all the way
To wonder at the sight: for till that day,
Through fear and wonder, that he nought could say,
O how great wonder would your thoughts deuoure,
And gazing wonder they their minds did fill;
Great wonder had the knight, to see the mayd
Till Alma him bespake, Why wonder yee
Ne wonder then, if that he were depriu'd
And all the world with wonder ouerspred;
And wonder of antiquitie long stopt his speach.
His wonder farre exceeded reasons reach,
Ne wonder, if these did the knight appall;
And with the wonder of her beames bright,
That wonder was to heare their trim consort.
For thy great wonder were it, if such shame
But who does wonder, that has red the Towre,
Wonder it is to see, in diuerse minds,
Ye wonder, how this noble Damozell
They were through wonder nigh of sense bereaued,
What wonder then, if one of women all did mis?
With wonder of her beauty fed their hungry vew.
That it a wonder of the world is song
What wonder then, if she were likewise carried?
Ne seeing could her wonder satisfie,
Did greatly wonder, ne could satisfie
Do greatly stand amaz'd at such vnwonted wonder.
That fild the lookers on attonce with ruth and wonder.
Well mote ye wonder how that noble Knight,
And drawne it was (that wonder is to tell)
Some laught for sport, some did for wonder shout,
And some that would seeme wise, their wonder turnd to dout.
Wonder it is that sudden change to see:
Ne certes wonder; for no powre of man
No wonder then, if that to winne the same
All that her saw with wonder rauisht weare,
And of his wonder made religion,
The Prince did wonder much, yet could not ghesse
Such mortall malice, wonder was to see
Ne wonder; for the heauens reuolution
That all men stood amaz'd, & at his might did wonder.
Are rapt with wonder, and with rare affright.
That all men wonder at her colours pride;
Not so great wonder and astonishment,
Ne to their force gaue way, that was great wonder,
With great amazement, & his thought with wonder fild.
And oft reioyce, and oft for wonder shout,
That what through wonder, & what through delight,
That who them sees, would wonder at their fray,
The knight at his great boldnesse wondered,
Whose bounty more then might, yet both he wondered.
So both at her, and each at other wondered.
That euen she her selfe much wondered
It is most straunge and wonderfull to fynd
And gazd vpon with gaping wonderment.
For that strange Dame, whose beauties wonderment
So stolen from their fancies wonderment;
All were the wounde so wide and wonderous,
Who wonders not, that reades so wonderous worke?
Far off he wonders, what them makes so glad,
And tassels gay. Wyde wonders ouer all
To proofe of passing wonders hath full often vsd.
Who wonders not, that reades so wonderous worke?
Then reasons reach, and oft hath wonders donne.
In vaine seekes wonders out of Magicke spell.
One of the worlds seuen wonders sayd to bee,
And halfe ashamed, wondred at the sight:
He wondred at her wisedome heauenly rare,
And wondred at so fowle deformed wight.
The knight much wondred at his suddeine wit,
Whereat he wondred much, and gan enquere,
No wonder if he wondred at the sight,
And wondred at his breathlesse hastie mood.
And wondred in his mind, what mote that monster make.
For much he wondred at that vncouth sight;
Him when the old man saw, he wondred sore,
The warlike Elfe much wondred at this tree,
And wondred at his endlesse exercise,
The wondred Argo, which in venturous peece
Much wondred Guyon at the faire aspect
They greatly wondred, whence so sumptuous guize
Whereat she wondred much, but would not stay
Stood gaping at their gate, and wondred them to see.
They wondred much, and shortly vnderstood,
Wondred to see her belly so vpblone,
Much wondred all men, what, or whence he came,
That all men wondred at the vncouth sight,
He wondred much. But th'other thus can say;
But wondred much at his so selcouth case,
At which he wondred much, when all those signes he fond.
Thus gazing long, at them much wondred he,
And wondred at their impacable stoure,
Wondred Agaue, Poris, and Nesï¿½a,
She wondred at the workemans passing skill,
And wondred much at Cupids iudg'ment wise,
Much wondred Calidore at this straunge sight,
And seeing it, much wondred at the sight;
The whiles vnwares away her wondring eye,
Who wondring much at that so sodaine fit,
Tho wondring long at those so straunge euents,
The maker selfe for all his wondrous witt,
Who thereat wondrous wroth, the sleeping spark
In charmes and magicke to haue wondrous might,
For she was wondrous faire, as any liuing wight.
But when he heard of harme, he wexed wondrous glad.
The Sarazin was stout, and wondrous strong,
Where was a Caue ywrought by wondrous art,
Such wondrous science in mans wit to raine
From lawlesse lust by wondrous grace
A wondrous way it for this Lady wrought,
His tayle was stretched out in wondrous length,
Of wondrous worth, and eke of wondrous mights,
Of wondrous worth, and eke of wondrous mights,
Well may I weene, your griefe is wondrous great;
For wondrous great griefe groneth in my spright,
For wondrous anguish in his hart it wrought,
Which flowed from his wounds in wondrous store,
Whose wondrous faith, exceeding earthly race,
Of wondrous worth, and vertue excellent,
A worke of wondrous grace, and able soules to saue.
As feeling wondrous comfort in her weaker eld.
And thereto added words of wondrous might:
Of wondrous beauty, and of bountie rare,
Adornd with gemmes and owches wondrous faire,
The wondrous workemanship of Gods owne mould,
Yet wondrous quick and persant was his spright,
Which to increase his wondrous greatnesse more,
And that more wondrous was, in either iaw
So wondrous force, from hand of liuing wight;
The griefe thereof him wondrous sore diseasd,
That nought so wondrous puissance might sustaine;
And then with words & weedes of wondrous might,
And wondrous strong by nature, and by skilfull frame.
Wondrous great prowesse and heroick worth
Came with them eke, all were they wondrous loth,
Thereat the Scarcrow wexed wondrous prowd,
So passing persant, and so wondrous bright,
And with her wondrous beautie rauisht quight,
A knight of wondrous powre, and great assay,
He wexed wondrous wroth, and said, Vile knight,
Thereat he wondrous glad, out of the path
Gaue wondrous great contentment to the knight,
Her face right wondrous faire did seeme to bee,
Of wondrous beautie, and of freshest yeares,
And sword saw not, he wexed wondrous woe:
But by your wondrous worth and warlike feat
To vew her castles other wondrous frame.
This parts great workmanship, & wondrous powre,
He now was growne right wise, and wondrous sage.
Ensample of his wondrous faculty,
And wondrous wit to menage high affaires,
Such wondrous powre did in that staffe appeare,
Who wondrous things concerning our welfare,
A worke of rare deuice, and wondrous wit.
The wondrous myrrhour, by which she
The royall Mayd woxe inly wondrous glad,
But wondrous massie and assured sound,
I in my fathers wondrous mirrhour saw,
Which the late world admyres for wondrous monime[n]ts.
Deepe busied bout worke of wondrous end,
And wondrous ruth to all, that shall it heare.
For whom he wondrous pensiue grew in mind,
Subdew, through conquest of your wondrous might,
Who in her sleepe (a wondrous thing to say)
She weend, and wondrous gladnesse to her hart applyde.
She there deuiz'd a wondrous worke to frame,
To errant knights be commun: wondrous sore
With great amazement of so wondrous sight,
Another plant, that raught to wondrous hight,
His halfen eye he wiled wondrous well,
The foolish man thereat woxe wondrous blith,
But he them both outran a wondrous space,
O wondrous skill, and sweet wit of the man,
Wondrous delight it was, there to behould,
In his diuine resemblance wondrous lyke:
That wondrous sight faire Britomart amazed,
And euerie looke was coy, and wondrous quaint,
And all the way with wondrous griefe of mynd,
And wondrous chast of life, yet lou'd of Knights & Lords.
By wondrous skill, and many hidden wayes,
But wondrous paine, that did the more enhaunce
And smote the other with so wondrous might,
The charet decked was in wondrous wize,
With which they wrought such wondrous maruels there,
His wondrous worth declared in all mens view.
With which she wondrous deeds of arms atchieued,
Vnder his arme, as seeming wondrous glad,
Cast into sundry shapes by wondrous skill,
And glisters wide, as als' of wondrous Bath,
And wondrous sholes, which may of none be red.
And with magnificke might and wondrous wit
And wondrous riches by his innouation.
She heard a wondrous noise below the hall.
Wherewith though wondrous wroth, and inly burning,
A wondrous vision, which did close implie
Could ought on earth so wondrous change haue wrought,
Such wondrous powre hath wemens faire aspect,
So faire a creature, and so wondrous bold,
Is wondrous strong, and hewen farre vnder ground
And wondrous noyse, as if that there were some,
She humbly thankt him for that wondrous grace,
Yet wondrous faire she was, and richly clad
For both were wondrous practicke in that play,
Had not a wondrous chaunce his reskue wrought,
As he the art of words knew wondrous well,
Through tempering of her words & lookes by wondrous skill.
Yet deckt with wondrous giftes of natures grace,
And wondrous ioy felt in her spirits thrall:
A looking glasse, right wondrously aguiz'd,
But wondrously begotten, and begonne
But wondrously they were begot, and bred
He was therewith right wondrously dismayd,
So wondrously now chaung'd, from that she was afore.
Doe serue a Queene, that not far hence doth wone,
Wherein ye haue great glory wonne this day,
Disdaind to loose the meed he wonne in fray,
In medicine, that else hath to thee wonne
Are wonne with pitty and vnwonted ruth,
He had in armes abroad wonne muchell fame,
Her children deare, whom he away had wonne:
Then wonne from death, she bad him tellen plaine
And he the stoutest knight, that euer wonne?
Not far away (quoth he) he hence doth wonne
But will at last be wonne with battrie long,
Be wonne, to spoyle the Castle of his health?
Be wonne their rightfull causes downe to tread:
Gan faile, but by her helpe the top at last he wonne.
But when thou famous victorie hast wonne,
In which he hath great glorie wonne, as I heare tell.
Where you a Saint with Saints your seat haue wonne:
To come, where vile Acrasia does wonne,
Till I that false Acrasia haue wonne;
That I that Ladie to my spouse had wonne;
Bycause he wonne; the other because hee
Was wonne: So matter did she make of nought,
That hath so many haughtie conquests wonne?
Or where hast thou thy wonne, that so much gold
He Easterland subdewd, and Danmarke wonne,
Are not firme land, nor any certein wonne,
Where daungers dwelt, and perils most did wonne,
Of all the which they honour euer wonne,
But when she mote not thereunto be wonne,
Do many famous Knightes and Ladies wonne,
Of which great worth and worship may be wonne;
To make his wonne, low vnderneath the ground,
Enioy the crowne, which they from Britons wonne
Rich strond to trauell, whereas he did wonne,
How that a noble hunteresse did wonne,
That in the same did wonne some liuing wight.
To steale away, that I with blowes haue wonne,
There was his wonne, ne liuing wight was seene,
Yet was soone wonne his malice to relent,
Where wearie wandring they long time did wonne,
That had from death to life him newly wonne.
And by no meanes would to his will be wonne,
But chose emongst the iolly Satyres still to wonne.
And braue exploits which great Heroes wonne,
And eke because his loue he wonne by right:
So hast thou to thy selfe false honour often wonne.
This hand her wonne, this hand shall her defend.
Ne which of them did winne, ne which were wonne.
Which Ferrau late from Braggadochio wonne,
Whom formerly he had in battell wonne,
But still the Knights of Maidenhead the better wonne.
That lately turneyd, had the wager wonne:
That bore the Hebene speare, as wonne in fight.
Her claym'd, by him in battell wonne long sens:
Or doe you here within this forrest wonne,
And wonne her will to suffer him depart;
He to it drew, to weet who there did wonne;
Vnto his wonne, and with her mournefull muse
And eke the famous prize of beauty from them wonne.
Through many perils wonne, and many fortunes waide.
Through which this shield of loue I late haue wonne,
Which Ladies loue I heard had neuer wonne
By whom those old Heroes wonne such fame;
And also those which wonne in th'azure sky?
Who all the West with equall conquest wonne,
A cursed cruell Sarazin doth wonne,
As fortune fell; yet litle lost or wonne:
For ought or nought be wonne vnto her will,
Her vassall to become, if she him wonne in fight.
And all the wayes she sought, his loue for to haue wonne.
There let her wonne farre from resort of men,
After that them in battell he had wonne.
And entraunce wonne. Streight th'other fled away,
That in these woods amongst the Nymphs dost wonne,
As by thy worth thou worthily hast wonne,
In which a worthy auncient Knight did wonne:
A saluage man, which in those woods did wonne,
And by good fortune the plaine champion wonne:
Of which he grace and glory wonne alwaies,
Gaue it to Coridon, and said he wonne it well.
He backe returned to his rusticke wonne,
But what befell her in that theeuish wonne,
The readie way vnto that theeuish wonne,
So led this Knight his captyue with like conquest wonne.
Emongst them all sate he, which wonned there,
Vntill she came where wonned his Belphebe faire.
And therein wonned twenty valiant Knights;
And wonned there, where now Yorke people dwell;
Which wonned in a rocke not farre away,
Prince Arthur is, that wonnes in Faerie lond;
Here wonnes Acrasia, whom we must surprise,
Where most she wonnes, whe[n] she on earth does dwel.
Of all that on this earthly compasse wonnes:
There is a mighty man, which wonnes here by
The fairest wight that wonneth vnder skye,
For he ne wonneth in one certaine stead,
He wonneth in the land of Fayeree,
She wonneth in the forrest there before.
With him to wend vnto his wonning neare:
Ay wont in desert darknesse to remaine,
Wherein the Hermite dewly wont to say
Who oft is wont to trouble gentle Sleepe.
As still are wont t'annoy the walled towne,
What frayes ye, that were wont to comfort me affrayd?
And for her Dwarfe, that wont to wait each houre;
Vnder them neuer sat, ne wont there sound
When Witches wont do penance for their crime)
And thrise nine hundred Aues she was wont to say.
Wont to robbe Churches of their ornaments,
Ne euer wont in field, ne in round lists to fight.
That wont in charet chace the foming Bore;
The sacred Nymph, which therein wont to dwell,
The same to wight he neuer wont disclose,
The force, which wont in two to be disperst,
Both feet and face one way are wont to lead.
Which in that stately building wont to dwell.
Were wont to riue steele plates, and helmets hew,
Ay wont to laugh, when them I heard to cry,
Wont on a staffe his feeble steps to stay,
Was wont him once to disple euery day:
He cryde, as raging seas are wont to rore,
As wont ye knights to seeke aduentures wilde,
Of armes was wont to fight, yet nathemoe
Of whom high Ioue wont whylome feasted bee,
That women wont in warres to beare most sway,
As Ladies wont, in pleasures wanton lap,
There the wise Merlin whylome wont (they say)
That whilome wont in women to appeare?
Are wont to cleaue vnto the lowly clay,
There wont faire Venus often to enioy
But in vaine sheows, that wont yongknights bewitch,
As was his wont in forrest, and in plaine;
Whereon faire Florimell was wont to ride,
Where she was wont her Sprights to entertaine
Ne euer is he wont on ought to feed,
That erst all entrers wont so cruelly to scorch.
And to her bed, which she was wont forbeare,
Such is thy wont, that still when any Knight
But she as Fayes are wont, in priuie place
Did not as others wont, directly fly
Are wont, before they may to heauen flie,
As was his wont; so weening way to make
An huge great speare, such as he wont to wield,
That whylome wont to be the victors meed;
Whilome it was (as Faeries wont report)
She with the pleasant Graces wont to play.
The which he neuer wont to combe, or comely sheare.
That whylome in your minde wont to despise them all.
In which he wont the relickes of his feast,
Which wont to stop the mouth thereof, that none
And his faire lockes, that wont with ointment sweet
As was her wont, thinking to let her weet
And that which wont to vanquish God and man,
Which in Star-read were wont haue best insight,
And next to him old Saturne, that was wont be best.
To tast of ioy, and to wont pleasures to retourne.
As was the wont of warlike knights of yore,
With his strange weapon, neuer wont in warre,
With which he wont to stirre vp battailous alarmes.
As women wont, but with deepe sighes, and singulfs few.
Which still was wont with Artegall remaine;
Those mighty palmes, the which ye wont t'embrew
All times haue wont safe passage to afford
Yet not, as women wont in dolefull fit,
Of which he in faire weather wont to take great store.
Are wont in Princes courts to worke great scath and hindrance.
That whylome wont to doe so many quake,
In which she wont to harbour happily:
Then it was wont, through comfort of this noble knight.
To whom he wont shew all the shame he might,
As he was wont, and chang'd from hand to hand,
With which he wont to fight, to iustifie his wrong.
With which he wont to launch the saluage hart
As they are wont vnto Latonaes sonne,
Is wont to cut off all, that doubt may breed,
Not wont on foote with heauy armes to trace,
Them wont to weare, and wend on foot for need,
Was wont his howres and holy things to bed;
As women wont their guilefull wits to guyde;
The whyles his saluage page, that wont be prest,
As he is wont at each Saint Valentide,
Which wont doe suit and seruice to his might;
As they are wont in faire sunshynie weather,
Handmaides of Venus, which are wont to haunt
For which the Graces that here wont to dwell,
Where wont the shepheards oft their pypes resound,
Which with those gentle shepherds here I wont to lead.
Weening their wonted entrance to haue found
Or wonted feare of doing ought amis,
That may restore you to your wonted well?
And backe returning tooke her wonted way,
Againe his wonted angry weapon proou'd:
Henceforth sir knight, take to you wonted strength,
Aboue his wonted pitch, with countenance fell,
Nathlesse with wonted rage he him aduaunced neare.
If wonted force and fortune do not much me faile.
Adieu, but nimbly ran her wonted course
And by the way, as was her wonted guize,
And their sweet skill in wonted melody;
Forceth it swell aboue his wonted mood,
From courtly blisse and wonted happinesse,
That now had chang'd her former wonted hew:
Hauing through stirring loosd their wonted band,
Gan dight him selfe vnto his wonted sinne;
In these wild woods, as was her wonted ioy,
His wonted warlike weapons all he broke,
Ne ought mote make him change his wonted tenor,
Till on a day, as in his wonted wise
The Prince on foot, not wonted so to fare;
The morrow next about the wonted howre,
All mindlesse of her wonted modestie,
But her the Prince through his well wonted grace,
Their pleasant friskes, and loath their wonted food;
That in short space his wonted chearefull hew
Not with amaze, as women wonted bee,
With raynes, or wonted rule, as well he knew.
Gins to looke vp, and with fresh wonted grace
An yearely solemne feast she wontes to make
In woods, in waues, in warres she wonts to dwell,
(As wonts the Tartar by the Caspian lake,
With which he wonts the Stygian realmes inuade,
Wherewith the Craftesman wonts it beautify,
In her great iron charet wonts to ride,
And eke the rocke, in which he wonts to dwell,
Fearing least she your loues away should woo,
And whether he did woo, or whether he were woo'd.
That he is not the while in state to woo;
This is the wandring wood, this Errours den,
The which at last out of the wood them brought.
But euery hill and dale, each wood and plaine
It fortuned out of the thickest wood
Which softly ecchoed from the neighbour wood;
Through vnaduized rashnesse woxen wood;
That on their rustie bits did champ, as they were wood.
Within the wood were dauncing in a rownd,
And worship her as Goddesse of the wood;
But to the wood she goes, to serue her turne,
Which through the wood loud bellowing, did rebownd,
She wandred many a wood, and measurd many a vale.
His speare of heben wood behind him bare,
Till with his cruell clawes he snatcht the wood,
Beholds her Nymphes, enraung'd in shadie wood,
That through the wood reecchoed againe,
Throughout the wood, that ecchoed againe,
The wood is fit for beasts, the court is fit for thee.
Pursew her steps, through wild vnknowen wood;
And calme the tempest of his passion wood;
He woo'd her thus: Pryene (so she hight)
Now gan Pyrrochles wex as wood, as hee,
And in frayle wood on Adrian gulfe doth fleet,
Clothed with leaues, that none the wood mote see
Emongst the shepheard swaynes, then wexeth wood & yond.
Yet was she woo'd of many a gentle knight,
For not of wood, nor of enduring bras,
Of that same wood it fram'd was cunningly,
At last as nigh out of the wood she came,
And to the brim with Colt wood did it fill,
Banisht from Princely bowre to wastfull wood:
There shall a Lyon from the sea-bord wood
Th'vsurped crowne, as if that he were wood,
Within that wood there was a couert glade,
With that he would haue fled into the wood;
Long thus I woo'd her with dew obseruance,
The driest wood is soonest burnt to dust.
Through many a wood, and many an vncouth way,
The wood they enter, and search euery where,
And euery wood, and euery valley wyde
Seeking aduentures in the saluage wood,
Which she with her long fostred in that wood,
But riued were like rotten wood a sunder,
Of two grim lyons, taken from the wood,
